## Appendix A — Which reviewer when

The reviewer roster is a per-project decision (it depends on which plugins
you have installed). Map each role below to a concrete `Agent` invocation
once — usually the agent name shipped by `pr-review-toolkit` or a similar
review-focused plugin you've adopted.

| Reviewer role | Use when | How to invoke |
|---|---|---|
| Language-strictness reviewer | Type/lint/strictness review of recently changed code (TypeScript, Go, Rust, etc.). | `Agent` tool with the relevant subagent (e.g. a TS-strict reviewer from your installed plugins). |
| Security reviewer | Auth, permission, credential-handling, or PHI/PII-adjacent changes. | `Agent` tool. |
| Architecture / design-pattern reviewer | Adding services or evaluating refactors. | `Agent` tool. |
| Silent-failure / error-handling reviewer | Catch blocks, fallback logic, swallowed errors. | `pr-review-toolkit:silent-failure-hunter` (default; substitute equivalent). |
| Data-migration reviewer | DB migration safety, ID mappings, schema changes. | `Agent` tool. |

This table is a placeholder per role; fill in the concrete agent name for
your stack once. When the agent suite you use changes, edit this file
(not `docs/methodology.md`). `docs/methodology.md` §I cites this appendix.
